<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Screen" class="currentChild" href="Screen">Screen</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
The portion of a computer monitor or a <a title="Cathode-Ray Tube" href="Cathode-Ray_Tube">cathode-ray tube</a> on which the image is displayed. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In process photography, a <em>screen</em> is a sheet of film with a particular set of dot patterns that is used to convert a <a title="continuous-tone" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/continuous-tone">continuous-tone</a> image into a <a title="Halftone" href="Halftone">halftone</a>, or a series of discrete dots of varying density. The term <em>screen</em> can also be used as a verb which means to produce a halftone from a continuous-tone image. (See <a title="Halftone" href="Halftone">Halftone</a>.) 
</p>
<p id="l5">
In digital halftone production, <em>screen</em> refers to the <a title="Screen Algorithms" href="Screen_Algorithms">screen algorithms</a> which convert the stored gray levels of the original image to the proper pattern of dots upon output. 
</p>
